docs.abstract: The giant retailer will begin requiring lettuce and spinach suppliers to contribute to a blockchain database that can rapidly pinpoint contamination.
docs.snippet: The giant retailer will begin requiring lettuce and spinach suppliers to contribute to a blockchain database that can rapidly pinpoint contamination.
docs.lead_paragraph: When dozens of people across the country got sick from eating contaminated romaine lettuce this spring, Walmart did what many grocers would do: It cleared every shred off its shelves, just to be safe.

headline.main: From Farm to Blockchain: Walmart Tracks Its Lettuce
headline.print_headline: From Farm to Blockchain: Walmart Tracks Its Lettuce

byline.original: By Michael Corkery and Nathaniel Popper

docs.abstract: The Ad Council — along with G.E., Google, IBM, Microsoft and Verizon — is trying to encourage girls ages 11 to 15 to get involved in science, technology, engineering and math.
docs.snippet: The Ad Council — along with G.E., Google, IBM, Microsoft and Verizon — is trying to encourage girls ages 11 to 15 to get involved in science, technology, engineering and math.
docs.lead_paragraph: Bonnie Ross, head of Microsoft’s Halo game studio, says, “You have the power to bring new worlds to life.” Maya Gupta, a Google research scientist, advises, “Don’t just solve the problem, write the code.” And Lisa Seacat DeLuca, a distinguished engineer at IBM, suggests, “If you can imagine it, it’s possible.”

headline.main: Role Models Tell Girls That STEM’s for Them in New Campaign
headline.print_headline: Convincing Girls That Tech, Science and Robots Are Up Their Alley
